<p><b>Curium</b> (<a href="./International_Phonetic_Alphabet" title="International Phonetic Alphabet">IPA</a>: <span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA">/ˈkjuːriəm/</span>) is a <a href="./Synthetic_element" title="Synthetic element">synthetic element</a> in the <a href="./Periodic_table" title="Periodic table">periodic table</a> that has the symbol <b>Cm</b> and <a href="./Atomic_number" title="Atomic number">atomic number</a> 96. A <a href="./Radioactive_decay" title="Radioactive decay">radioactive</a> <a href="./Metal" title="Metal">metallic</a> <a href="./Transuranic_element" title="Transuranic element">transuranic element</a> of the <a href="./Actinide" title="Actinide">actinide</a> series, curium is produced by bombarding <a href="./Plutonium" title="Plutonium">plutonium</a> with <a href="./Alpha_particle" title="Alpha particle">alpha particles</a> (<a href="./Helium" title="Helium">helium</a> <a href="./Ion" title="Ion">ions</a>) and was named for <a href="./Maria_Sklodowska-Curie" title="Maria Sklodowska-Curie">Marie Curie</a> and her husband <a href="./Pierre_Curie" title="Pierre Curie">Pierre</a>.</p>
